{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17536871","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17536871"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:11:11+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:11:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15827"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15827","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15827"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.3,0.03,0.2,0.32,0.15]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8518"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62776"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8518","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8518"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15827"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48224"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"44"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1027"},{"type":"tags","id":"3105"},{"type":"tags","id":"4631"},{"type":"tags","id":"4978"},{"type":"tags","id":"5817"},{"type":"tags","id":"5826"},{"type":"tags","id":"9222"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20444"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43595"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62776","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/62776"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 47-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic for review of chronic pain management. He sustained multiple traumatic injuries in a motor vehicle accident three years ago and requires ongoing opioid therapy, including both slow-release and immediate-release formulations. He has a history of depression and anxiety but has previously declined psychological support after bad experiences with cognitive behavioural therapy (CBT). Today, he expresses interest in seeing a psychologist again to help manage his pain. He does not take any medications apart from his prescribed opioids.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. He describes his current pain as 7/10 and reports significant catastrophizing thoughts about his condition.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following psychological approaches would be most beneficial for this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Psychologically informed physical therapy","Exposure therapy","Eye Movement Desensitization and Reprocessing","Acceptance and Commitment Therapy","Supportive counselling"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with chronic pain and demonstrates readiness to engage with psychological support despite previous negative experiences. While CBT has the strongest evidence base for chronic pain management, his previous poor experience suggests an alternative approach may be more suitable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcceptance and Commitment Therapy\u003C/strong\u003E (ACT) is particularly well-suited for chronic pain management, especially in patients who have not responded to CBT. Rather than focusing on challenging thoughts (as in CBT), ACT helps patients accept their pain while committing to actions aligned with their values. This approach may be more palatable for someone who has previously rejected traditional cognitive approaches.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPsychologically informed physical therapy\u003C/strong\u003E combines physical therapy with psychological principles. While this can be valuable, this patient\u0027s high pain levels and catastrophizing thoughts suggest he needs a more focused psychological intervention first.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExposure therapy\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily used for specific phobias and anxiety disorders. While it can help with fear of movement in chronic pain, it does not address the broader psychological aspects of pain management that this patient requires.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEye Movement Desensitization and Reprocessing\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily used for processing trauma. While the patient may have trauma from his accident, his primary needs are pain management and developing psychological flexibility.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESupportive counselling\u003C/strong\u003E, while helpful for building therapeutic alliance, lacks the structured approach and specific pain management strategies that this patient needs. His catastrophizing thoughts require a more targeted intervention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EACT\u0027s focus on psychological flexibility and value-based action makes it particularly suitable for chronic pain patients who have not responded to CBT. It helps them develop a different relationship with their pain while pursuing meaningful life activities, which is especially relevant given this patient\u0027s current motivation for change.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Acceptance and Commitment Therapy (ACT) is an evidence-based approach for chronic pain that focuses on psychological flexibility and living meaningfully despite pain","Active engagement in psychological therapy is more important than the specific modality chosen","Cognitive behavioural therapy (CBT) has the strongest evidence base amongst psychotherapy for chronic pain"],"references":["Driscoll MA, Edwards RR, Becker WC, Kaptchuk TJ, Kerns RD. Psychological interventions for the treatment of chronic pain in adults. Psychological Science in the Public Interest. 2021 Sep;22(2):52-95. Available online at ; https://journals.sagepub.com/doi/abs/10.1177/15291006211008157"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48224"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15827"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48224","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/48224"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-18T20:16:53+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-18T20:17:08+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8518"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62776"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"44","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/44"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude79","name":"Pain Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"78","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/78"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level III","synonyms":null,"description":"Apply, analyze, evaluate, and create (implementing, organizing, and critiquing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"head